RESEARCH EXPERIENCE AND INTERESTS 

 
Artificial intelligence, machine learning, biologically inspired computing, cognitive science, and complex 
systems.  
 

 
Ph.D. in Computer Science, 1990, University of Michigan.   

GRADUATE EDUCATION 

Dissertation advisor:  Douglas R. Hofstadter  
Dissertation title: Copycat: A Computer Model of High-Level Perception  and Conceptual Slippage in 
Analogy-Making. 
 

PROFESSIONAL EMPLOYMENT 

 

Professor, Portland State University, Department of Computer Science, 9/04–present.  
 
External Professor, Santa Fe Institute, 2000–present. 
 
Professor, 7/04–9/04; Associate Professor, 8/02–7/04, OGI School of Science and Engineering, Oregon Health & 
Science University, Department of Computer Science and Engineering. 
 
Staff Member, Santa Fe Institute, 10/00–8/02.   
 
Technical Staff Member, Los Alamos National Laboratory, Biophysics Group, 9/99–9/00.  
 
Research Professor and Director of the Adaptive Computation Program, Santa Fe Institute, 6/92–8/99.  
 
Postdoctoral Scholar, University of Michigan, Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, 
9/90–6/92. 
 

	

 
 
 
 

